      "SAML 2.0 is an XML-based enterprise authentication standard supported by major IdPs like Microsoft Entra ID (Azure AD), Okta, and Google Workspace. The LMS registers as an SP and validates SAML Assertions (signed XML tokens) from the IdP. Its strength is maturity in enterprise environments; its weakness is XML parsing overhead and complexity in mobile implementations.",
      "OAuth 2.0 is technically an authorization (not authentication) protocol. However, OIDC (OpenID Connect), which adds an ID token layer on top of OAuth 2.0, has become the de facto modern SSO standard. JWT-based, lightweight, and fast — it integrates naturally with REST APIs and is ideal for mobile apps and SPAs.",
      "Protocol selection criteria: ① Legacy IdP supporting only SAML → SAML 2.0 ② Modern SaaS/mobile-first environments → OIDC ③ Heavy external API integration → OAuth 2.0 + OIDC combo. Enterprises and government agencies tend to prefer SAML 2.0, while startups and SaaS companies lean toward OIDC.",
